# forms

SpiderFlow forms — Typeform-class multi-step forms (lead capture, NPS / CSAT surveys, intake forms, signup wizards) for tenant sites. Built on the same `booking_flows` engine that powers SpiderBook, discriminated by `kind='form'`.

**Status: developer / agent preview (Wave 2).** The dashboard editor for business users (P1.M1) is in active development; for now, forms are authored end-to-end via CLI / MCP / VSCode extension.

**Exposed via:** `@spideriq/mcp@1.13.0` (kitchen-sink) — **20 `form_*` tools + `booking_flow_list` with `?kind=` filter**. **NOT in `@spideriq/mcp-publish`** — see [the caveat below](#mcp-package-caveat).

## What you ship with this

- A multi-step form widget (15+ field types: short_text, long_text, email, phone, number, dropdown, checkbox, picture_choice, rating, nps, opinion_scale, date, file_upload, statement, yes_no)
- A standalone route at `/book/{flow_id}` on the tenant's primary domain
- An embed loader at `https://embed.spideriq.ai/v1/loader.js` (3 KB gzip) — drops a form into any third-party page in one `<script>` tag, two declarative shapes (inline + popup)
- Conditional logic: rules with variables, hidden fields (URL-param capture for utm_*, etc), client-side structural validation
- Copy-paste embed snippets generated by `form_get_embed_snippet`
- A test-submit path (`?test=true`) for QA without polluting real lead data

## When to use

- A tenant needs a multi-step form: lead capture, signup wizard, intake form, NPS / CSAT survey
- You're migrating a Typeform form to SpiderPublish (cost reduction; agent-driven authoring)
- You need to embed a form on an external site (Webflow, Shopify, WordPress, Framer, plain HTML)
- You want hidden-field capture for tracking parameters (utm_source, ref, ...)
- The form needs branching logic (e.g. "if user picks 'Yes', show fields A-C; else show D-E")

## When NOT to use

- Single-question subscribe form / newsletter signup → use a page with a `form` block (lighter)
- Calendar / appointment slot picking → use [booking](../booking/) — that's what cal.com event-types are for
- Long-form content authoring (blog posts, docs) → use [content-platform](../content-platform/)
- E-commerce checkout → no inventory / payment model in SpiderFlow forms

## MCP package caveat

The 20 `form_*` tools live in **`@spideriq/mcp@1.13.0`** (the kitchen-sink package, 144 tools total) — **not** in `@spideriq/mcp-publish@1.12.1` (the atomic publish package, 124 tools).

This is deliberate: Antigravity, Claude Desktop, and Codex-on-Responses silently drop MCP servers that report more than 128 tools. `mcp-publish` stays under the ceiling so it loads cleanly across every IDE; the kitchen-sink `mcp` package opts into the higher tool count.

**If you're using the starter kit's default `.mcp.json` (which points at `mcp-publish`), the `form_*` tools won't appear.** Three options:

1. **Switch the existing entry:** edit `.mcp.json` and replace `@spideriq/mcp-publish` with `@spideriq/mcp@1.13.0`. You get every tool (publish + booking + forms + mail + leads + gate + admin) at the cost of the higher tool count.
2. **Add a second MCP server:** keep `mcp-publish` as the default, add `mcp` as `spideriq-forms` (or similar) and only enable it in form-authoring sessions.
3. **Wait for `@spideriq/mcp-forms`:** an atomic forms-only package is on the P1.6 follow-up list — it'll let you pull just the forms surface without the kitchen-sink overhead.

A future starter-kit release will surface this choice in `.mcp.json` directly.

## End-to-end: from zero to an embedded form

```bash
# 1. List existing flows (to avoid name collisions)
spideriq form list --kind form           # via the new ?kind= filter
# OR via MCP: booking_flow_list({ kind: "form" })

# 2. Create a draft form with two initial fields
spideriq form create \
  --name "Free trial signup" \
  --business <business_uuid> \
  --field 'fields=[{"id":"q1","type":"email","label":"Your work email","required":true},{"id":"q2","type":"short_text","label":"Company name","required":true}]'
# → returns flow_id

# 3. Add a third field via MCP
form_add_field({
  flow_id: "<flow_id>",
  field: { id: "q3", type: "dropdown", label: "Team size", options: [
    { label: "1-10",   value: "small"  },
    { label: "11-50",  value: "medium" },
    { label: "51+",    value: "large"  }
  ]}
})

# 4. Add conditional logic: if team_size = "large", jump to enterprise field
form_add_logic_rule({
  flow_id: "<flow_id>",
  rule: {
    when: { field_id: "q3", op: "equals", value: "large" },
    then: { action: "jump_to", field_id: "q_enterprise" }
  }
})

# 5. Validate the whole flow (client-side; no API call)
form_validate({ flow: <full flow blob> })
# → { errors: [], warnings: [] }

# 6. Test-submit (with ?test=true — no real lead row created)
form_test_submit({
  flow_id: "<flow_id>",
  answers: { q1: "test@example.com", q2: "Acme Corp", q3: "small" }
})

# 7. Publish (2-phase confirm)
spideriq form publish <flow_id>
# → preview + confirm_token
spideriq form publish <flow_id> --confirm <token>
# → status: active

# 8. Get the embed snippet (local-only — no API call)
spideriq form embed-snippet <flow_id> --mode popup --button-text "Get Free Trial"
# → <script async src="https://embed.spideriq.ai/v1/loader.js"></script>
#   <button data-spiderflow-flow="<flow_id>" data-spiderflow-mode="popup"
#           data-spiderflow-trigger-text="Get Free Trial">Get Free Trial</button>

# 9. Paste into any third-party page (Webflow, Shopify, WordPress, plain HTML)
```

## Backend caveats (current state)

These will be resolved in P1.M1 / P1.M2; documented inline so agents work around them gracefully:

| Issue | Workaround |
|---|---|
| `form_create` requires `business_id` (FK constraint) | Pass any business UUID owned by the brand. Backend will make this optional for `kind='form'`. |
| `form_publish` requires Cal.com `title` / `length_minutes` / `team_id` | Pass any non-empty title, `length_minutes=1`, `team_id=0`. Backend will go kind-aware. |
| `form_test_submit ?test=true` honoured only for `LOAD_TEST_CLIENT_ID` | Until backend extends honour, use a real flow with a unique answer payload + clean up the test row manually. |
| Server-side `duplicate` and `validate` endpoints don't exist | Both work — `form_duplicate` composes client-side as `get + create`; `form_validate` runs entirely client-side against the locked schema. |

## VSCode extension (SpiderPublish 0.2.0+)

If you're using the [SpiderPublish VSCode extension](https://github.com/SpiderIQ/SpiderPublish/tree/main/designer-kit), forms are first-class:

- **Pull:** `SpiderPublish: Pull Content` enumerates every `kind='form'` row and writes each to `./forms/<flow_id>.json`
- **Edit:** open any `./forms/*.json`; inline form validator catches 14 rule classes (R0–R14) with red squiggles
- **Push:** `SpiderPublish: Push Content` includes form rows alongside pages / posts / components
- **Preview:** `SpiderPublish: Preview Form` opens `/book/<flow_id>` in your default browser

The 0.2.0 VSIX ships with the extension. Marketplace publish (vsce + ovsx) is in Wave 3.

## Embed loader API

The loader (`embed.spideriq.ai/v1/loader.js`) exposes `window.SpiderFlow`:

- `window.SpiderFlow.version` — running loader version (self-reported from package.json)
- `window.SpiderFlow.create(element, options)` — programmatic mount
- `window.SpiderFlow.scan()` — re-scan the DOM for `[data-spiderflow-flow]` (call after SPA route changes)
- `window.SpiderFlow.destroyAll()` — tear down every mounted iframe

Configuration via `data-*` attributes:
- `data-spiderflow-flow="<flow_id>"` (required)
- `data-spiderflow-mode="inline|popup"` (default: inline)
- `data-spiderflow-domain="https://forms.spideriq.ai"` (override the form-render domain)
- `data-spiderflow-trigger-text="Open Form"` (popup only)
- `data-spiderflow-on-complete="window.myCallback"` (dotted-path lookup; no `eval`)
- `data-spiderflow-auto-open="true"` (popup only — open immediately on mount)
- `data-spiderflow-hide-headers="true"` (suppress form chrome for a tighter embed)
- `data-prefill-<key>="<value>"` (any number; populates hidden fields by key)

Two embed shapes:

```html
<!-- Inline: replace a div with an iframe -->
<div data-spiderflow-flow="<flow_id>" data-spiderflow-mode="inline"></div>
<script async src="https://embed.spideriq.ai/v1/loader.js"></script>

<!-- Popup: button → modal iframe (lazy-loaded; iframe doesn't fetch until click) -->
<button data-spiderflow-flow="<flow_id>" data-spiderflow-mode="popup"
        data-spiderflow-trigger-text="Open Form">Open Form</button>
<script async src="https://embed.spideriq.ai/v1/loader.js"></script>
```

Origin validation is built in — `event.source === iframe.contentWindow && event.origin === configured_domain` before any side-effect. Two embeds on one page never cross-talk (each drops messages whose `flowId` doesn't match).

